argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Next year, presumably on the earlier side of th=
e first quarter,
<em>Washington Post </em>publisher and C.E.O. <strong>Will Lewis </strong>i=
ntends to announce that he has appointed acting executive editor <strong>Ma=
tt Murray</strong> as the newsroom=E2=80=99s <em>permanent</em> chief, acco=
rding to sources familiar with his plans. The news, which Will has been del=
aying for unspecified reasons, will bring an anticlimactic end to a long an=
d tortured recruitment effort at a storied paper that=E2=80=94as you know, =
dear reader=E2=80=94has endured a rather miserable and ignominious few
years of financial irresponsibility, soul-searching, and chaos.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Murray, after all, was <em>not </em>Will=E2=80=99s first choice. I=
n June, he had <em>tried</em>, quite inelegantly, to appoint his fellow Bri=
t <strong>Rob Winnett</strong> to the post while transitioning the lacklust=
er incumbent <strong>Sally Buzbee</strong> out of the role=E2=80=94only to =
be all but <em>mutinied</em> by veterans who chafed at the
incursion of a Fleet Street sensibility at their august institution. Instea=
d, Will enlisted Murray, his former <em>Wall Street Journal</em> top editor=
, to man the rudder until he could appoint someone else, at which point Mur=
ray was slated to become head of a =E2=80=9Cthird newsroom=E2=80=9D focused=
 on new digital projects and innovations.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It was =
an open secret that Murray, who had sort of been pottering around
since his <em>Journal </em>exit, coveted the job and thought he had an outs=
ide shot. Lewis nevertheless cast about for alternatives, presumably a swas=
hbuckling innovator prepared to become his wingman to truly reinvent the in=
stitution. But he and executive search firm Egon Zehnder engaged a now fami=
liar rolodex of obvious (too obvious, really) candidates from across the <e=
m>Post</em>=E2=80=99s competitive landscape=E2=80=94including <em>New York =
Times </em>masthead fixtures <strong>Carolyn Ryan </strong>and
<strong>Cliff Levy</strong>, and former <em>Post </em>editors <strong>Anne =
Kornblut </strong>and <strong>Steven Ginsberg</strong>=E2=80=94while also g=
iving consideration to internal candidates like <strong>Matea Gold </strong=
>and Murray, himself. As <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9=
pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUNXY4MXNBbDJqVVRycVB5RHFZTT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaH=
R0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvZ2VvcmdlLXN0ZXBoYW5vcG91bG9zLXJldXBzLXdpdGgtYWJjLW5ld=
3MtYWZ0ZXItdHJ1bXAtc2V0dGxlbWVudC8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUr=
QnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYyMCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnR=
lbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMiUyRjIwJT=
JGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3Vzd=
G9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2=
YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwMjI4MDR9/e2eeff68a0ef250def50eb821f=
8a3007c69bd1b27bab6cbe7bbf5184bd7f6b8e" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;=
color:#d40000;">I=E2=80=99ve noted</a>, it seemed that the folks he might h=
ave been able to recruit weren=E2=80=99t the ones he <em>really
</em>wanted, and the ones he wanted weren=E2=80=99t<em> really </em>interes=
ted. The whole process felt rather depressing.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Th=
is may have been inevitable, given the heavy pall of negativity and ennui t=
hat had set in on the newsroom since the latter <strong>Fred Ryan </strong>=
era, and which Will only exacerbated with his irreverent disregard for trad=
itional <em>Post</em>ian decorum, beyond just the paper=E2=80=99s
decision to pull their presidential endorsement. Of course, he was indisput=
ably correct when he told the proud <em>Post </em>newsroom that no one was =
reading their stuff=E2=80=94well, it was a slight exaggeration=E2=80=94but =
the affront only made them <em>more</em> dubious about his ability to lead =
the paper. At the same time, he didn=E2=80=99t exactly articulate a vision =
or announce what the <em>Post </em>should be doing <em>differently</em>, no=
r how he intended to reverse its nearly $100 million annual revenue
losses. Could you blame Carolyn Ryan for preferring to stick around at the =
<em>Times </em>and play the long <strong>Joe Kahn </strong>waiting game?</p=
