sy parties. After all, nothing motivates members to do their jobs quite so =
much as the threat of being stuck in Washington well into Christmas recess.=
 And so they usually manage, at the eleventh hour, to pull a continuing res=
olution out of Santa=E2=80=99s sack, declare victory, and fly home.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">In that sense at least, this week was typical.
Yes, a bill <em>finally</em> passed in a bipartisan vote on Friday night, b=
ut this year=E2=80=99s fire drill felt different. Over the past three days,=
 we=E2=80=99ve seen unelected bureaucrat slash bureaucrat slash billionaire=
 <strong>Elon Musk </strong>blow up a bipartisan compromise bill, a veritab=
le conservative mutiny over Speaker <strong>Mike Johnson</strong>=E2=80=99s=
 replacement bill, and the emergence of a bizarre side plot involving <stro=
ng>Donald</strong> <strong>Trump</strong>=E2=80=99s demand to delay or even
<em>eliminate</em> the debt ceiling. With each passing hour, Johnson=E2=80=
=99s chances of holding on to the speaker=E2=80=99s gavel seemed to slip, u=
ntil=E2=80=94suddenly=E2=80=94a funding bill sailed through the House with =
overwhelming bipartisan support. Stay tuned in the weeks ahead to find out =
Johnson=E2=80=99s fate. But this round of chaos has been on a scale even De=
mocrats didn=E2=80=99t see coming. <br/><br/>So, is the G.O.P. honeymoon al=
ready over, less than two months after they secured the Washington power tr=
ifecta? I put this
question to a plugged-in Capitol Hill Republican operative, who quipped: =
=E2=80=9CThey walked into the honeymoon pregnant=E2=80=9D with the burdens =
of Trump, Musk, and the tight House margin. Another Hill Republican compare=
d the House G.O.P.=E2=80=99s lame duck to a rodeo: =E2=80=9CEight seconds i=
s not enough to ride the bull.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Johnson spent the past few =
days navigating a noxious morass of egos, ideology, and confusion. <em>Ever=
yone</em> on the Hill
was, for much of the week, either angry with Johnson, actively making his l=
ife hell, or some combination thereof. Obviously, his tormentors-in-chief w=
ere Musk and Trump, who tanked his original bipartisan bill via separate so=
cial media tantrums. Meanwhile, House Democratic leader <strong>Hakeem Jeff=
ries</strong>, who has had a good working relationship with Johnson, was fu=
rious after Johnson backed out of the initial funding deal they=E2=80=99d s=
truck. Members of Johnson=E2=80=99s own conference spent the
latter half of the week getting in front of any camera they could find to c=
riticize his every decision and lack of communication.=C2=A0</p></div>
