argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In the third installment of Puck=E2=80=99s conv=
ersation series about A.I.,
presented by Meta, <strong>Baratunde</strong> <strong>Thurston</strong> cha=
tted with our resident legal expert, <strong>Eriq Gardner</strong>, about t=
he myriad ways that A.I. is impacting the entertainment industry, generatin=
g a palpable mixture of fear, curiosity, and genuine excitement=E2=80=A6</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;"><strong><em>Baratunde Thurston</em></strong><strong>: Wha=
t=E2=80=99s jumping out to you right now regarding how A.I. is
impacting the entertainment industry?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Eriq=
 Gardner</em>: I feel like we=E2=80=99re still in the phase where we=E2=80=
=99re just dipping our toes in. I think everyone is curious, a little scare=
d, and excited=E2=80=94as many adjectives as you can think of. We still hav=
en=E2=80=99t seen any kind of transformative commercial use for it. But wha=
t we have seen is a bunch of cool aspects that shock people and make it cle=
ar that this
is our future and there=E2=80=99s no denying it. But everyone is still aski=
ng each other, <em>What=E2=80=99s next? </em>It=E2=80=99s generated so much=
 conversation=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s the number one topic whenever I speak to=
 anyone in the industry=E2=80=94but no one is quite certain about it. They =
feel like they have a map that gives them a general direction, but not nece=
ssarily the G.P.S. coordinates to where everything is going.</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;"><strong>Where are you
seeing any breakdown in the =E2=80=9Cresist first=E2=80=9D versus =E2=80=9C=
embrace first=E2=80=9D approach to A.I.?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">From =
my standpoint, I generally think people are on the same page right now. But=
 you=E2=80=99re starting to sense some fissures. You have people who=E2=80=
=99ve experimented with the use of it, and then there are people who are qu=
ite defensive and don=E2=80=99t want A.I. encroaching on their art. It seem=
s that people who are less
entrenched in the industry have nothing to lose, so they=E2=80=99re gonna t=
ry this thing out and see what happens. Whereas, for people who have a big =
stake in the industry=E2=80=94there=E2=80=99s a lot more to fear.=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">For instance, you might think that very famous actors have=
 the opportunity to license their faces and not show up on set as much and =
leverage their fame, and that A.I. might help them exploit many more
opportunities. But if you=E2=80=99re a background actor, you=E2=80=99re in =
trouble. It=E2=80=99s not just about the haves and have-nots. It=E2=80=99s =
also about who aligns best to what the technology is capable of doing.</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><a=
